Location

In the raw but de-duplicated data, we have 14,454,058 points in the current data dump. After filtering out observations with missing fields, sample_time values outside of the appropriate ranges, points with an accuracy greater than or equal to 500 meters, and points that dont correspond to a twin, we have 9,392,250 points on 618 individuals. Lets visualize the distribution of the number of points per twin.

cleaned_twin_locations %>% group_by(user_id) %>% summarize(n = n()) %>% filter(n < 50000) %>% left_join(user_data, by = c("user_id" = "alternate_id")) %>% ggplot(aes(x = n, color = app_type)) + geom_density()

This is the opposite of what was expected - since Android records every five minutes and iOS only when the phone moves. This may be because location tracking was deployed to the Android app after the iOS app - meaning that Android users will have fewer points. We can test this by looking at the mean density of location points for iOS vs.Android. Well need the length of time between first and last locations for each twin, converting from seconds to days.

first_last_locs <- cleaned_twin_locations %>% group_by(user_id) %>% summarize(first_point = min(sample_time), last_point = max(sample_time)) %>% mutate(duration_days = as.numeric(last_point - first_point)/60/60/24)

cleaned_twin_locations %>% group_by(user_id) %>% summarize(n = n()) %>% left_join(user_data, by = c("user_id" = "alternate_id")) %>% left_join(first_last_locs) %>% mutate(loc_density = n / duration_days) %>% ggplot(aes(x = loc_density, color = app_type)) + geom_density() + xlab('Points Per Day')
## Joining, by = "user_id"
## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

Clearly, we are getting far fewer points from most Android devices than we expect. Lets take a look at the distibution of the time between points.

results <- tibble()

for (twin in unique(cleaned_twin_locations$user_id)) {
  results2 <- cleaned_twin_locations %>% filter(user_id == twin) %>% arrange(sample_time) %>% left_join(user_data, by = c('user_id' = 'alternate_id')) %>% transmute(point_interval = lead(sample_time) - sample_time, app_type = app_type)
  results <- bind_rows(results, results2)
}
results %>% mutate(point_interval = point_interval + 1) %>% ggplot(aes(x = point_interval, fill = app_type)) + geom_histogram() + scale_x_log10()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 618 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

So, most Android points are falling where we expect - around five minutes, with a long tail where the phone stopped reporting for whatever reason. We also have a very large number of iOS points where sample_time was the same for consecutive points. This may have something to do with the algorithm used by iOS to trigger the reporting of a point. Lets try looking at physical distance between consecutive points.

results <- tibble()

for (twin in unique(cleaned_twin_locations$user_id)) {
  results2 <- cleaned_twin_locations %>% filter(user_id == twin) %>% arrange(sample_time) %>% left_join(user_data, by = c('user_id' = 'alternate_id')) %>% transmute(point_interval = distHaversine(cbind(lead(.$longitude), lead(.$latitude)), cbind(.$longitude, .$latitude)), app_type = app_type)
  results <- bind_rows(results, results2)
}
results %>% mutate(point_interval = point_interval + 1) %>% ggplot(aes(x = point_interval, fill = app_type)) + geom_histogram() + scale_x_log10()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 618 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

After doing a little investigating, it became clear that iOS has a lot of duplicates, not across all columns but across user_id, sample_time, latitude, and longitude. I have now modified src/location/clean_location_data.R to eliminate this issue.
